Let=E2=80=99s see:=09In 2016, Revlon Inc. borrowed $1.8 billion from some b=
anks and hedge funds using a seven-year  term loan secured by Revlon=E2=80=
=99s assets. Citibank NA advised on the loan and served as its administrati=
ve agent.=09In 2019 and 2020, Revlon took some of the collateral for the 20=
16 term loan and snuck it out, away from the lenders: It put much of its in=
tellectual property, including brands like American Crew, Elizabeth Arden, =
Almay and Mitchum, into new subsidiaries (generally called =E2=80=9CBrandCo=
=E2=80=9D) that did not secure the 2016 loan. It  borrowed some new money=
=C2=A0secured by those brands, and rolled some of the old term lenders into=
 the new facility in order to get them to vote to approve it. There were va=
rious shenanigans involved, including doing a new revolving loan under the =
2016 credit agreement in order to get just enough votes to approve the new =
deal. We have discussed   the basic form of this many   times before: If yo=
u are a company in trouble, you pay off 51% of your lenders to get them to =
approve hosing the other 49%. That=E2=80=99s what happened here: Revlon gav=
e some of its lenders a new loan with better security (those brands), makin=
g the security for the other lenders worse. (This is explained in more deta=
il  here.)=09The 2016 lenders who didn=E2=80=99t participate in the new Bra=
ndCo deal were annoyed: Their collateral had disappeared, and now they were=
 effectively junior to the 2020 lenders. They  sued Revlon, Citibank and va=
rious other people, claiming that the BrandCo deal violated the 2016 credit=
 agreement and was invalid. If they won =E2=80=A6=C2=A0I dunno, it would be=
 a mess if they won, but generally speaking if they won then they would get=
 those brands back as collateral for their loans.=09The day before they fil=
ed that lawsuit, Citi paid them off by accident. Oops! This was very funny =
and we have   talked about it a lot, but the gist is that Citi, as administ=
rative agent for the loan, was supposed to pass along a small interest paym=
ent from Revlon and accidentally paid off the whole loan with its own money=
.=09Citi politely asked the 2016 lenders for the money back, but the lender=
s were really mad at Citi for helping with the BrandCo transaction, so some=
 of them =E2=80=94=C2=A0who had gotten about $500 million of Citi=E2=80=99s=
 money =E2=80=94=C2=A0said no.=09Citi sued them and, somewhat shockingly,  =
 lost.=C2=A0=09Citi appealed. I assume Citi will win on appeal, but then I =
assumed they=E2=80=99d win in the trial court so who knows. The appeal is s=
till pending and could take a while.=09Meanwhile the thing everyone worried=
 about happened, and Revlon filed for bankruptcy last week.This raises vari=
ous wild questions. For instance: Who are the creditors on the 2016 term lo=
an, now? There are three main options:=09Citi: Citi paid off that $500 mill=
ion on Revlon=E2=80=99s behalf,=C2=A0so it presumably steps into the shoes =
of those creditors and has a $500 million bankruptcy claim against Revlon. =
(This is probably not worth $500 million: My Bloomberg screen shows the 201=
6 term loan trading below 30 cents on the dollar, while the 2020 BrandCo te=
rm loan looks to be in the 50s.)=09The original lenders: Maybe Citi will wi=
n on appeal, in which case the lenders=C2=A0will have to give back Citi=E2=
=80=99s $500 million, in which case Revlon will still owe them the money. =
=E2=80=9CLawyers for the repaid lenders in the bankruptcy court hearing on =
Thursday described their clients as only =E2=80=98contingent creditors=E2=
=80=99 who since they have already been repaid will not need to participate=
 in the bankruptcy fight unless the appeals court orders them to return the=
 cash to Citi,=E2=80=9D  reports Sujeet Indap at the Financial Times. But s=
ince it will presumably take a while to find out, they continue to have som=
e interest in the case.=09Nobody:=C2=A0Did Citi pay that $500 million on Re=
vlon=E2=80=99s behalf? Or did it pay the $500 million out of the goodness o=
f its heart, discharging Revlon=E2=80=99s obligation to the term lenders bu=
t not creating any new obligation to Citi? That seems ridiculous, but on th=
e other hand Revlon=C2=A0is=C2=A0in bankruptcy so it has an incentive =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0an obligation, almost =E2=80=94=C2=A0to minimize its debt load.=
Bloomberg=E2=80=99s Jeremy Hill and Eliza Ronalds-Hannon   reported last we=
ek:=C2=A0=E2=80=9CThere isn=E2=80=99t a lot of law on this,=E2=80=9D said E=
ric Talley, a Columbia University law professor who has studied the Citi-Re=
vlon debacle. =E2=80=9CRevlon would like nothing better than to wipe this d=
ebt off its books completely and have it be Citibank=E2=80=99s problem.=E2=
=80=9DThe so-called subrogation rights that Citigroup claims it has over th=
e $500 million loan principal are a common concept in insurance law, but ar=
e relatively untested in the world of finance, according to Talley. The lim=
ited precedent that exists probably falls in Citigroup=E2=80=99s favor, but=
 Revlon=E2=80=99s precarious financial position likely makes even a long-sh=
ot attempt to wipe out the debt worth considering, he said.=C2=A0In its lat=
est quarterly report, Revlon said it hasn=E2=80=99t taken a stance on Citig=
roup=E2=80=99s rights as creditor. It went a step further this week, saying=
 that if Citigroup ultimately loses its battle to reclaim the money, Revlon=
 =E2=80=9Creserve all rights and defenses with respect to any claim Citiban=
k may assert against=E2=80=9D the company.=C2=A0A successful challenge of C=
itigroup=E2=80=99s claim could erase almost 15% of Revlon=E2=80=99s $3.4 bi=
llion debt load in an instant, easing the company=E2=80=99s path out of ban=
kruptcy. But the scorched-earth tactic is far from a sure thing, and risks =
souring the company=E2=80=99s relationship with Citigroup, said Bloomberg I=
ntelligence analyst Phil Brendel, who believes the odds are against Revlon.=
I can=E2=80=99t imagine Revlon winning that argument, but I can easily imag=
ine them trying.But there is another wild question, which is: What about th=
at lawsuit to set aside the BrandCo deal? If the 2016 term loan lenders win=
 that argument, then their loan will get a higher recovery (they will have =
a claim on the BrandCo assets) and the 2020 lenders=C2=A0will get a lower r=
ecovery (they will have to share the BrandCo assets). But if they win their=
 Citi appeal, this doesn=E2=80=99t affect them at all: They already got pai=
d 100 cents on the dollar (by Citi), so they don=E2=80=99t care. They are =
=E2=80=9Conly =E2=80=98contingent creditors.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D Still, they=
