 =20
We have  talked a few  times recently about how people borrow money to=C2=
=A0do leveraged trading in decentralized finance, and how it differs from l=
everaged trading in traditional finance. One key difference is:=09In tradit=
ional finance, if you have borrowed money to buy some stocks, and the stock=
s have gone down, your broker will call you up and say =E2=80=9Chey could y=
ou post more collateral.=E2=80=9D Ideally you post the collateral and every=
thing is fine. Sometimes you don=E2=80=99t, and your broker sells the stock=
s at hopefully a high enough price to pay off your loan. But sometimes you =
say =E2=80=9Csorry, I can=E2=80=99t post any more collateral today, but I c=
an try tomorrow,=E2=80=9D and your broker=C2=A0gives you another day.=09In =
decentralized finance, if you have borrowed money (stablecoins)=C2=A0to buy=
 some crypto, and the crypto has gone down, a robot sells your crypto at ho=
pefully a high enough price to pay off your loan, automatically and without=
 bothering to call you.I have mostly emphasized that the traditional approa=
ch can be=C2=A0more generous to you, the borrower: Sometimes you don=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0pay back your loan, but your broker gives you more time. Why woul=
d the broker do this? Well, you might be a good customer, and the broker wo=
n=E2=80=99t want to make you mad. Or you might be a big=C2=A0fund, and the =
broker will think =E2=80=9Csure this=C2=A0position=C2=A0is undercollaterali=
zed but all in all they=E2=80=99re good for it.=E2=80=9D Or you might be so=
 big that the broker will think =E2=80=9Cif I liquidate this position it is=
 going to crash the market and cause a systemic crisis, whereas if I just g=
ive them another day to pay maybe everything will be fine.=E2=80=9D[2]=C2=
=A0Or you might say =E2=80=9Csorry, can=E2=80=99t make a margin call right =
now, I=E2=80=99m on vacation with limited cell service=E2=80=9D and your br=
oker might say =E2=80=9Cah we=E2=80=99ve all been there=E2=80=9D and give y=
ou another week. (True story: Once, when I was a banker, I sent a Brazilian=
 client a large margin call. They said =E2=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s Carnival, sorr=
y, try us next week.=E2=80=9D I gulped and waited. It worked out fine!)=C2=
=A0The crypto robots don=E2=80=99t do any of this sort of thinking. They ju=
st look at the collateral, look at the position, and if the collateral is t=
oo low they liquidate. The crypto system is often stricter, which is good (=
less buildup of systemic risk) and bad (harder to sleep).On the other hand,=
 the traditional approach can also be stricter. Sometimes your stocks=C2=A0=
haven=E2=80=99t=C2=A0gone down, and your broker calls you up and says =E2=
=80=9Chey we are changing our margining requirements and would like you to =
post more collateral.=E2=80=9D And if you say no, the broker will (eventual=
ly) liquidate your position.Why would the broker do this? Well, there might=
 be a new risk manager at your broker, and she might want more collateral. =
Or volatility might have gone up and your broker=E2=80=99s model now demand=
s more collateral. Or your stocks might have gone=C2=A0up, and your broker =
might say =E2=80=9Cthis position is so big that we need to manage the risk =
more strictly.=E2=80=9D Or your broker might have heard a rumor that you ar=
e in financial trouble. Or your broker might have heard a rumor that a bunc=
h of other investors are in trouble, so it is=C2=A0tightening up collateral=
 across the board. Or something else.Can=C2=A0your broker do this? Does you=
r contract with your broker allow them to just call you up for more collate=
ral? The short answer is, sure, probably; brokers are good at protecting th=
emselves. The longer answer is that you are all embedded in a fuzzy system =
of repeat players and you cannot ignore your broker=E2=80=99s demands forev=
er, even if your current contract favors you.=C2=A0If your broker asks you =
for more collateral then, in the long run, your choices are (1) post more c=
ollateral or (2) find another broker;=C2=A0either=C2=A0of those approaches =
accomplishes the broker=E2=80=99s essential goal of reducing its risk expos=
ure.=C2=A0This is actually an=C2=A0element of  the Archegos Capital Managem=
ent story: When Credit Suisse Group AG called Archegos for more collateral,=
 it was=C2=A0not=C2=A0because Archegos=E2=80=99s stocks had gone down; they=
 had gone up, and Credit Suisse took a closer look at its margin provisions=
 and realized they were not great, so it called up Archegos and asked to ch=
ange those provisions. Archegos said =E2=80=9Cwe=E2=80=99ll get back to you=
=E2=80=9D and then imploded, oops. But the basic story is that Credit Suiss=
e tried to adjust its margin provisions on the fly to address newly salient=
 risks, and Archegos was at least in theory willing to work with Credit Sui=
sse on that.Meanwhile in decentralized finance, if you wake up one morning =
to realize that a whale has built up a huge position in an increasingly vol=
atile market, and that your margin provisions are not adequate to protect y=
ou if you need to close the position, what do you do? I mean =E2=80=A6=C2=
=A0kind of the same sorts of ad hoc things that you=E2=80=99d do in traditi=
onal finance, but you get a lot more grief for it.Solend is a DeFi=C2=A0len=
ding platform on the Solana blockchain. It =E2=80=A6=C2=A0discovered? =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0that it has one =E2=80=9Cwhale=E2=80=9D client who has borrowed=
 a huge amount of stablecoins from Solend to fund a position in Solana=E2=
=80=99s native SOL token. If the price of SOL falls too far, the Solend sma=
rt contract will automatically start liquidating the whale=E2=80=99s positi=
on in a way that will apparently overwhelm market liquidity, crater the pri=
ce of SOL and cause huge losses for Solend and its own depositors (the peop=
le who put up the stablecoins that Solend is lending to the whale). CoinDes=
k reports:The anonymous wallet at the heart of the crisis had deposited 95%=
 of Solend=E2=80=99s entire SOL pool and represented 88% of USDC borrowing.=
 But Solend=E2=80=99s single-largest user came dangerously close to a massi=
ve margin call with SOL=E2=80=99s cratering price. If SOL hit $22.30, the p=
rotocol would automatically liquidate up to 20% of the whale=E2=80=99s coll=
ateral.To avoid this, Solend decided to amend the smart contract to let Sol=
end=E2=80=99s team take over the whale=E2=80=99s position and start liquida=
ting it in over-the-counter transactions=C2=A0before=C2=A0it hits the margi=
n trigger. To do this, it put the proposal to a vote of its decentralized a=
utonomous organization; from Solend=E2=80=99s blog post:Any action we take =
(including inaction) has a set of trade offs to consider. There is no perfe=
ct solution. With that in mind, the action we believe would result in the b=
est outcome is as follows:Enact special margin requirements for large whale=
s that represent over 20% of borrows. If a user=E2=80=99s borrows amount to=
 over 20% of all borrows for the Main Pool, a special liquidation threshold=
 of 35% is required. This policy will go into effect upon approval of the p=
roposal.Grant emergency power to Solend Labs to temporarily take over the w=
hale=E2=80=99s account so the liquidation can be executed OTC and avoid pus=
hing Solana to its limits. This would be done via a smart contract upgrade.=
 Emergency powers will be revoked once the whale=E2=80=99s account reaches =
a safe level.The proposal passed, but in a hasty way that led to lots of ob=
jections, so they walked it back: Solend introduced another proposal to res=
cind the first one, and then a third to create new position limits to mitig=
ate this risk in a more mechanical way.=C2=A0I suppose you could conclude s=
omething along the lines of:=09In traditional finance, this stuff is manage=
d through a combination of contractual remedies, background legal and equit=
able principles, and fuzzy relationships and reputations.=09In decentralize=
d finance, people like to say that =E2=80=9Ccode is law=E2=80=9D:=C2=A0Ever=
ything is supposed to be transparent and deterministic; smart contracts spe=
cify exactly what happens in every case.=09Code is not law. Sometimes the s=
mart contracts do not=C2=A0cover the cases you end up caring about, or they=
 do, but not in the way anyone wants.=09Nothing else is law either, so you =
make things up from scratch.Elsewhere in crypto leverage =E2=80=A6=C2=A0uh,=
 I dunno, there=E2=80=99s a lot of it?=09=E2=80=9CBabel Finance, the distre=
ssed crypto lender which froze withdrawals on Friday, said it won a repriev=
e on debt repayments as it battles to survive a tumultuous slump in cryptoc=
urrency markets.=E2=80=9D=09=E2=80=9CCelsius Network Ltd. will  need more t=
ime to stabilize its liquidity and operations, the embattled crypto lending=
 platform said in a blog post after it froze deposits last week.=E2=80=9D=
=09=E2=80=9CCryptocurrency-focused hedge fund  Three Arrows Capital Ltd. ha=
s hired legal and financial advisers to help work out a solution for its in=
vestors and lenders, after suffering heavy losses from a broad market sello=
ff in digital assets, the firm=E2=80=99s founders said on Friday.=E2=80=9D=
=09=E2=80=9CCrypto lending platform  BlockFi announced that it has secured =
a $250 million revolving credit facility from FTX, BlockFi CEO Zac Prince s=
aid in a tweet on Tuesday, and the company subsequently announced in a pres=
s release.=E2=80=9DAlso here is=C2=A0a sentence that I love: =E2=80=9CDue t=
o hostile market conditions, Bancor=E2=80=99s Impermanent Loss Protection i=
s temporarily paused.=E2=80=9D I don=E2=80=99t know why I find it so funny.=
 It=E2=80=99s, like, doubly temporary. In the long run everything is fine! =
In the short run, things are troubling, but only temporarily and also imper=
manently.=E2=80=9CImpermanent loss=E2=80=9D basically means that if you act=
 as a market maker in crypto, and the market moves away from you, you lose =
money. (There is nothing particularly impermanent about this; the name is=
=C2=A0just a hilarious bit of branding.) Bancor runs an automated market ma=
ker system that uses customers=E2=80=99 crypto deposits to make markets, an=
d when its customers have =E2=80=9Cimpermanent loss,=E2=80=9D Bancor prints=
 more of its own BNT tokens and gives them to the customers to make them wh=
ole. That is a system that works great as long as crypto is generally going=
 up: Bancor can keep printing tokens, which keep getting more valuable, whi=
ch means it can pay everyone who loses money on a trade. When the token goe=
s down it stops working. From Bancor=E2=80=99s blog post:BNT rewards effect=
ively have a double-cost:They depreciate the BNT value, resulting in imperm=
anent loss on the network.This IL is compensated with additional BNT emissi=
ons, causing further value depreciation.The intuition is that if the price =
of BNT goes down, Bancor will print more BNT to make the BNT holders whole =
for the loss. But printing more BNT to give to BNT holders makes the price =
go down more, etc. This is not the same mechanic as  what happened to Terra=
USD, but it has a family resemblance. (Actually it has a family resemblance=
 to a lot of crypto mechanics, in which people are often incentivized to ho=
ld some token by printing more of that token, and new money flowing into th=
e system counteracts the inflationary effects of that printing =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0until the new money stops flowing.) And so now Bancor=E2=80=99s imperman=
ent loss protection is temporarily paused.=C2=A0
