      A tax trade
   =20
 =20
Here is a schematic tax trade. In=C2=A0US federal income taxation, long-ter=
m capital gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0net gains on assets held for more than a yea=
r =E2=80=94=C2=A0are taxed at low rates, while short-term capital gains =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0less than a year =E2=80=94=C2=A0are taxed at high rates. The tr=
ade is:=09All year, generate a lot of short-term capital gains, for instanc=
e by operating a market-making business that turns over an inventory of sto=
cks and options many times each day.=09On Jan. 1, buy 100 stocks, and short=
 100 different but correlated stocks.=09On Dec. 30, close out the losing po=
sition from Step 2: If the stocks are up, buy back the ones you shorted; if=
 they=E2=80=99re down, sell the ones you bought. Now you have short-term ca=
pital losses that offset your short-term capital gains.=09The next Jan. 2, =
close out the winning position from Step 2: If stocks are up, sell the ones=
 you bought; if they=E2=80=99re down, buy back the ones you shorted. Now yo=
u have long-term capital gains that offset your short-term capital losses.=
=09The net pre-tax result is that=C2=A0your trades from Steps 2 through 4=
=C2=A0offset each other: Nothing has happened, economically, between Step 2=
 and Step 4, and you are just left with your trading gains from Step 1.=C2=
=A0=09The net post-tax result is that you have transformed the short-term c=
apital gains from Step 1 into the long-term capital gains in Step 4, saving=
 yourself a lot of taxes.This is a schematic simple version, and in the rea=
l world various nuances and complications are required. Of course, you=C2=
=A0could imagine an even simpler version: In Step 2, instead of buying some=
 stocks and shorting some other stocks, you could just buy a ton of one sto=
ck and short a ton of=C2=A0the same stock. But this is frowned upon: It is =
called a =E2=80=9Cstraddle=E2=80=9D in tax law, and you can=E2=80=99t use l=
osses on a straddle to offset other income.[3] You basically want to do a t=
rade that is correlated enough to=C2=A0work=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0to generate=
 roughly offsetting gains and losses without too much risk of the losses to=
tally swamping the gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0but uncorrelated enough to get by t=
he tax authorities.=C2=A0Here is a fun ProPublica story about Jeffrey Yass =
and the other partners of Susquehanna International Group, which allegedly =
does this sort of stuff:Since 2011, IRS records show, a partnership called =
Susquehanna Fundamental Investments has been the source of the majority of =
long-term gains for Yass and his partners. Every year, it channeled hundred=
s of millions in long-term gains to them, while also providing hundreds of =
millions in short-term losses.Year after year, the gains and losses rose an=
d fell roughly in tandem, as if one were a near reflection of the other. In=
 2015, for example, Susquehanna Fundamental produced $774 million in long-t=
erm gains and $787 million in short-term losses for Yass. In 2017 it was $9=
40 million in long-term gains and $902 million in short-term losses. =E2=80=
=A6Susquehanna Fundamental held billions of dollars of individual stocks su=
ch as Google, Wells Fargo and, as it happens, Coca-Cola. These stocks were =
among the largest companies in the S&P 500 index.Meanwhile, the fund also h=
eld a large bet against the S&P 500. In essence, it held a bet against many=
 of those exact same stocks.On its face, the fund actually lost money for Y=
ass: Over eight years, it registered $5.4 billion in losses against $5 bill=
ion in gains =E2=80=94 a net loss before taxes. But by transforming the tax=
 rate on so much income, it delivered $1.1 billion in tax savings, and Yass=
 came out way ahead.This is not quite as lovely as  the Renaissance Technol=
ogies approach of putting all the short-term trades into a basket =E2=80=9C=
owned=E2=80=9D by an investment bank and then buying an =E2=80=9Coption=E2=
=80=9D on that basket, but I guess it does the job.
