      Universal owners
   =20
 =20
I  wrote on Thursday about how the interests of universal asset owners =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0people who own 10% (or whatever) of every public company =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0differ from the interests of concentrated owners of a single, say,=
 oil company. In particular, I noted:=09Owners of a single oil company will=
 want it to drill more oil when prices are high, because it can sell that o=
il at high prices. Owners of every oil company will want them all to exerci=
se some capital discipline, since if they=C2=A0all drill more oil prices wi=
ll go down. Universal ownership, the theory goes, is anti-competitive: Univ=
ersal owners will want to keep margins high rather than increase production=
.=09Owners of a single oil company will want it to drill more oil, but univ=
ersal owners will be more concerned about the effects of climate change on =
all their other portfolio companies, and so will want to reduce drilling al=
l around.Several people pointed out an offsetting=C2=A0consideration: Unive=
rsal owners should want lower oil prices right now, because in the actual w=
orld high oil prices seem to be driving inflation and economic worry. If oi=
l prices were lower, then all the other companies that the universal owners=
 own would be making more money now, though in the long run they=E2=80=99d =
have to worry about climate change etc.That seems right.=C2=A0Which set of =
concerns dominates is=C2=A0an empirical question. We were talking about thi=
s on Thursday because the founder of Continental Resources Inc. wants to ta=
ke his company private to avoid meddling public investors, and my sense is =
that in general US oil-company managers feel like their public investors ar=
e more interested in capital discipline and environmental, social and gover=
nance concerns than they are in drilling more oil.=C2=A0One point here=C2=
=A0is that the meaning of =E2=80=9Cenvironmental, social and governance=E2=
=80=9D investing can change as facts in the world change. In a world where =
inflation is low, the economy is booming and Russia has not invaded Ukraine=
, drilling oil can look like a bad-for-ESG business. In a world where infla=
tion is high, recession is looming and high oil prices fund a Russian invas=
ion, drilling for oil can look pretty noble.
