tom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> times</a> recently about how pe=
ople borrow money to=C2=A0do leveraged trading in decentralized finance, an=
d how it differs from leveraged trading in traditional finance. One key dif=
ference is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; m=
argin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In traditional finance=
, if you have borrowed money to buy some stocks, and the stocks have gone d=
own, your broker will call you up and say =E2=80=9Chey could you post more =
collateral.=E2=80=9D Ideally you post the collateral and everything is fine=
. Sometimes you don=E2=80=99t, and your broker sells the stocks at hopefull=
y a high enough price to pay off your loan. But sometimes you say =E2=80=9C=
sorry, I can=E2=80=99t post any more collateral today, but I can try tomorr=
ow,=E2=80=9D and your broker=C2=A0gives you another day.</li>=09<li style=
=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">In decentralized finance, if you have borrowed mon=
ey (stablecoins)=C2=A0to buy some crypto, and the crypto has gone down, a r=
obot sells your crypto at hopefully a high enough price to pay off your loa=
n, automatically and without bothering to call you.</li></ol><p style=3D"ma=
rgin: 16px 0;">I have mostly emphasized that the traditional approach can b=
e=C2=A0more generous to you, the borrower: Sometimes you don=E2=80=99t=C2=
=A0pay back your loan, but your broker gives you more time. Why would the b=
roker do this? Well, you might be a good customer, and the broker won=E2=80=
=99t want to make you mad. Or you might be a big=C2=A0fund, and the broker =
will think =E2=80=9Csure this=C2=A0<em>position=C2=A0</em>is undercollatera=
lized but all in all they=E2=80=99re good for it.=E2=80=9D Or you might be =
so big that the broker will think =E2=80=9Cif I liquidate this position it =
is going to crash the market and cause a systemic crisis, whereas if I just=
 give them another day to pay maybe everything will be fine.=E2=80=9D[2]=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Or you might say =E2=80=9Csorry, can=E2=
=80=99t make a margin call right now, I=E2=80=99m on vacation with limited =
cell service=E2=80=9D and your broker might say =E2=80=9Cah we=E2=80=99ve a=
ll been there=E2=80=9D and give you another week. (True story: Once, when I=
 was a banker, I sent a Brazilian client a large margin call. They said =E2=
=80=9Cit=E2=80=99s Carnival, sorry, try us next week.=E2=80=9D I gulped and=
 waited. It worked out fine!)=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The cry=
pto robots don=E2=80=99t do any of this sort of thinking. They just look at=
 the collateral, look at the position, and if the collateral is too low the=
y liquidate. The crypto system is often stricter, which is good (less build=
up of systemic risk) and bad (harder to sleep).</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px=
 0;">On the other hand, the traditional approach can also be stricter. Some=
times your stocks=C2=A0<em>haven=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>gone down, and your br=
oker calls you up and says =E2=80=9Chey we are changing our margining requi=
rements and would like you to post more collateral.=E2=80=9D And if you say=
 no, the broker will (eventually) liquidate your position.</p><p style=3D"m=
argin: 16px 0;">Why would the broker do this? Well, there might be a new ri=
sk manager at your broker, and she might want more collateral. Or volatilit=
y might have gone up and your broker=E2=80=99s model now demands more colla=
teral. Or your stocks might have gone=C2=A0<em>up</em>, and your broker mig=
ht say =E2=80=9Cthis position is so big that we need to manage the risk mor=
e strictly.=E2=80=9D Or your broker might have heard a rumor that you are i=
n financial trouble. Or your broker might have heard a rumor that a bunch o=
f other investors are in trouble, so it is=C2=A0tightening up collateral ac=
ross the board. Or something else.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>Can=
=C2=A0</em>your broker do this? Does your contract with your broker allow t=
hem to just call you up for more collateral? The short answer is, sure, pro=
bably; brokers are good at protecting themselves. The longer answer is that=
 you are all embedded in a fuzzy system of repeat players and you cannot ig=
nore your broker=E2=80=99s demands forever, even if your current contract f=
avors you.=C2=A0If your broker asks you for more collateral then, in the lo=
ng run, your choices are (1) post more collateral or (2) find another broke=
r;=C2=A0<em>either=C2=A0</em>of those approaches accomplishes the broker=E2=
=80=99s essential goal of reducing its risk exposure.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">This is actually an=C2=A0element of <a href=3D"https://lin=
