</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a schematic tax trade. In=C2=
=A0US federal income taxation, long-term capital gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0net g=
ains on assets held for more than a year =E2=80=94=C2=A0are taxed at low ra=
tes, while short-term capital gains =E2=80=94=C2=A0less than a year =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0are taxed at high rates. The trade is:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-=
type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-=
bottom: 5px;">All year, generate a lot of short-term capital gains, for ins=
tance by operating a market-making business that turns over an inventory of=
 stocks and options many times each day.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom:=
 5px;">On Jan. 1, buy 100 stocks, and short 100 different but correlated st=
ocks.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">On Dec. 30, close out the lo=
sing position from Step 2: If the stocks are up, buy back the ones you shor=
ted; if they=E2=80=99re down, sell the ones you bought. Now you have short-=
term capital losses that offset your short-term capital gains.</li>=09<li s=
tyle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The next Jan. 2, close out the winning positio=
n from Step 2: If stocks are up, sell the ones you bought; if they=E2=80=99=
re down, buy back the ones you shorted. Now you have long-term capital gain=
s that offset your short-term capital losses.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bo=
ttom: 5px;">The net <em>pre-tax</em> result is that=C2=A0your trades from S=
teps 2 through 4=C2=A0offset each other: Nothing has happened, economically=
, between Step 2 and Step 4, and you are just left with your trading gains =
from Step 1.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The net <em>pos=
t-tax</em> result is that you have transformed the short-term capital gains=
 from Step 1 into the long-term capital gains in Step 4, saving yourself a =
lot of taxes.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is a schematic sim=
ple version, and in the real world various nuances and complications are re=
quired. Of course, you=C2=A0could imagine an even simpler version: In Step =
2, instead of buying some stocks and shorting some other stocks, you could =
just buy a ton of one stock and short a ton of=C2=A0<em>the same stock</em>=
. But this is frowned upon: It is called a =E2=80=9Cstraddle=E2=80=9D in ta=
x law, and you can=E2=80=99t use losses on a straddle to offset other incom=
e.[3] You basically want to do a trade that is correlated enough to=C2=A0<e=
m>work=C2=A0</em>=E2=80=94=C2=A0to generate roughly offsetting gains and lo=
sses without too much risk of the losses totally swamping the gains =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but uncorrelated enough to get by the tax authorities.=C2=A0</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is a fun <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloom=
bergbusiness.com/click/28128683.261603/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cucHJvcHVibGljYS5vcmcv=
YXJ0aWNsZS9qZWZmLXlhc3Mtc3VzcXVlaGFubmEtdGlrdG9rLXRheC1hdm9pZGFuY2U/607f07c=
