style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> wrote on Thursday</a> about how the=
 interests of universal asset owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0people who own 10% (or =
whatever) of every public company =E2=80=94=C2=A0differ from the interests =
of concentrated owners of a single, say, oil company. In particular, I note=
d:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16=
px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Owners of a single oil company =
will want it to drill more oil when prices are high, because it can sell th=
at oil at high prices. Owners of every oil company will want them all to ex=
ercise some capital discipline, since if they=C2=A0<em>all </em>drill more =
oil prices will go down. Universal ownership, the theory goes, is anti-comp=
etitive: Universal owners will want to keep margins high rather than increa=
se production.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Owners of a single =
oil company will want it to drill more oil, but universal owners will be mo=
re concerned about the effects of climate change on all their other portfol=
io companies, and so will want to reduce drilling all around.</li></ol><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Several people pointed out an offsetting=C2=A0cons=
ideration: Universal owners should want lower oil prices right now, because=
 in the actual world high oil prices seem to be driving inflation and econo=
mic worry. If oil prices were lower, then all the other companies that the =
universal owners own would be making more money now, though in the long run=
 they=E2=80=99d have to worry about climate change etc.</p><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">That seems right.=C2=A0Which set of concerns dominates is=C2=
=A0an empirical question. We were talking about this on Thursday because th=
e founder of Continental Resources Inc. wants to take his company private t=
o avoid meddling public investors, and my sense is that in general US oil-c=
ompany managers feel like their public investors are more interested in cap=
ital discipline and environmental, social and governance concerns than they=
 are in drilling more oil.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One point =
here=C2=A0is that the meaning of =E2=80=9Cenvironmental, social and governa=
nce=E2=80=9D investing can change as facts in the world change. In a world =
where inflation is low, the economy is booming and Russia has not invaded U=
kraine, drilling oil can look like a bad-for-ESG business. In a world where=
 inflation is high, recession is looming and high oil prices fund a Russian=
 invasion, drilling for oil can look pretty noble.</p><table class=3D"heade=
